uding WordPress.</span></li><li><span>Pete Mall <a title="Pete Mall''s post about plugin UI" href="http://developersmind.com/2011/04/05/wordpress-tabbed-metaboxes/  ">blogged</a> about updating the UI on one of his plugins to fall in line with the default WordPress UI.</span></li></ul><p>Next up are tutorials to feed your WordPress powered brain:</p><ul><li><span>WPBeginner has a tutorial up showing how to show off your <a title="Showing off popular posts in WordPress" href="http://www.wpbeginner.com/wp-tutorials/display-popular-posts-by-day-week-month-and-all-time-in-wordpress/">most popular posts</a> in WordPress.</span></li><li><span>Kevin Muldoon posted about <a title="How to add navigation menus in WordPress" href="http://www.wpmods.com/how-to-add-navigation-menu-to-wordpress-theme">how to add navigation menus</a> to your WordPress site. He also showed how to retrieve <a title="How to retrieve comments across a multisite network" href="http://www.wpmods.com/get-comments-across-mult-site-network">comments across a multisite network</a> this week too.</span></li><li><span>While we&#8217;re on multisite tutorials, WPEngineer shows <a title="How to retrieve a site''s ID" href="http://wpengineer.com/2188/view-blog-id-in-wordpress-multisite/">how to retrieve the blog id</a> of sites in a multisite network.</span></li><li><span>WPMU.org has a collection of <a title="Tips for speeding up your WordPress site" href="http://wpmu.org/speeding-up-your-wordpress-website-11-ways-to-improve-your-load-time/">tips for speeding up</a> your WordPress website.</span></li><li><span>Oli Dale has put together a tutorial showing how to take advantage of <a title="Using multiple=">multiple post thumbnail sizes</a> in WordPress.</span></li><li><span>Jeff Starr has a post up showing <a title="How to emulate Tumblr with WordPress post formats" href="http://digwp.com/2011/04/tumblr-links-post-formats/">how to emulate Tumblr</a> with the new WordPress post formats.</span></li><li><span>WinkPress has published an in depth tutorial series showing <a title="How to create a product review site with WordPress" href="http://winkpress.com/review-site/tutorial/  ">how to create a product review site</a> with WordPress.</span></li><li><span>Michael Martin talks about <a title="Using the Twitter API within WordPress" href="http://www.problogdesign.com/wordpress/how-to-use-the-twitter-api-in-wordpress/">using the Twitter API within WordPress</a>, a simple and efficient script that grabs the tweets, then displays them from Twitter.</span></li></ul><p>Finally, we have a few resources that you might want to bookmark:</p><ul><li><span>The organizers of WordCamp Melbourne <a title="WordCamp Melbourne survey results" href="http://melbourne.wordcamp.org.au/2011/04/08/wordcamp-melbourne-2011-feedback-survey-results/  ">shared their survey results</a> on their blog. If you&#8217;re participating in a WordCamp somewhere, these results might be interesting to you.</span></li><li><span>Brad Vincent assembled a list of <a title="Alternatives to Akismet" href="http://themergency.com/free-akismet-alternatives/  ">alternatives to Akismet</a> (hat tip <a title="Jeff Chandler found that link" href="http://www.wptavern.com/6-alternatives-to-akismet">Jeff</a> for finding that one).</span></li><li><span>JT Pratt has posted a collection of <a title="100 things you should know about WordPress" href="http://www.jtpratt.com/100-things-you-need-to-know-about-wordpress/  ">100 things</a> you should know about WordPress. That&#8217;s probably a good place to start if you aren&#8217;t sure what you don&#8217;t know yet.</span></li></ul><p>And that does it for links this week. If you&#8217;ve found others, be sure to drop them in the comments below. Or, if you have a link you think should be in next week&#8217;s roundup, feel free to <a title="Contact WPCandy" href="http://wpcandy.com/is/here">contact us</a>.</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16753">WordPress Community Links: Big stack of Dummies edition</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";}i:10;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:69:"WPCandy: Adii Pienaar interviewed, discusses the success of WooThemes";s:4:"guid";s:27:"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16756";s:4:"link";s:113:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/wpcandy/~3/Pehtp7CWtUM/adii-pienaar-interviewed-discusses-the-success-of-woothemes";s:11:"description";s:724:"<p></p><p>Adii Pienaar is a co-founder of WooThemes and well known member of the WordPress community. In this particular interview he discusses WooThemes&#8217; current growth, their plans for the future, and how his other projects are faring.</p><p>Adii is being interviewed by Charl Norman of the great <a href="http://www.bandwidthblog.com/2011/04/07/adii-woothemes-premium-wordpress-themes/">Bandwidth Blog</a>.</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16756">Adii Pienaar interviewed, discusses the success of WooThemes</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 09 Apr 2011 22:36:23 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:9:"Ryan Imel";}s:7:"summary";s:724:"<p></p><p>Adii Pienaar is a co-founder of WooThemes and well known member of the WordPress community. In this particular interview he discusses WooThemes&#8217; current growth, their plans for the future, and how his other projects are faring.</p><p>Adii is being interviewed by Charl Norman of the great <a href="http://www.bandwidthblog.com/2011/04/07/adii-woothemes-premium-wordpress-themes/">Bandwidth Blog</a>.</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16756">Adii Pienaar interviewed, discusses the success of WooThemes</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";}i:11;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:58:"Weblog Tools Collection: WordPress Plugin Releases for 4/9";s:4:"guid";s:40:"http://weblogtoolscollection.com/?p=9871";s:4:"link";s:73:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/weblogtoolscollection/UXMP/~3/fmuoQkBB-QY/";s:11:"description";s:1525:"<h3>New plugins</h3>\n<p><a href="http://tinsology.net/plugins/amazon-tools/"><strong>Amazon Tools</strong></a> allows you to integrate your WordPress blog with Amazon Web Services.</p>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/category-redirect-to-post-or-page/"><strong>Category Redirect to Post or Page</strong></a> allows you to easily redirect category links to a specific page, post, or even an outside url.</p>\n<h3>Updated plugins</h3>\n<p><a href="http://ocaoimh.ie/exploit-scanner/"><strong>Exploit Scanner</strong></a> searches the files on your website, and the posts and comments tables of your database for anything suspicious. It also examines your list of active plugins for unusual filenames.</p>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/health-check/"><strong>Health Check</strong></a> will perform a number of checks on your WordPress install to detect common configuration errors and known issues.</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.designchemical.com/blog/index.php/wordpress-plugins/wordpress-plugin-jquery-vertical-accordion-menu-widget/"><strong>jQuery Vertical Accordion Menu</strong></a> creates vertical accordion menus from any WordPress custom menu.</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.ivinco.com/software/wordpress-sphinx-search/"><strong>WordPress Sphinx Search</strong></a> allows to use Sphinx Search Server power to enable ultra-fast and feature-rich search on WordPress-based websites.</p>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/weblogtoolscollection/UXMP/~4/fmuoQkBB-QY" height="1" width="1" />";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Sat, 09 Apr 2011 13:00:27 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:10:"James Huff";}s:7:"summary";s:1525:"<h3>New plugins</h3>\n<p><a href="http://tinsology.net/plugins/amazon-tools/"><strong>Amazon Tools</strong></a> allows you to integrate your WordPress blog with Amazon Web Services.</p>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/category-redirect-to-post-or-page/"><strong>Category Redirect to Post or Page</strong></a> allows you to easily redirect category links to a specific page, post, or even an outside url.</p>\n<h3>Updated plugins</h3>\n<p><a href="http://ocaoimh.ie/exploit-scanner/"><strong>Exploit Scanner</strong></a> searches the files on your website, and the posts and comments tables of your database for anything suspicious. It also examines your list of active plugins for unusual filenames.</p>\n<p><a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/health-check/"><strong>Health Check</strong></a> will perform a number of checks on your WordPress install to detect common configuration errors and known issues.</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.designchemical.com/blog/index.php/wordpress-plugins/wordpress-plugin-jquery-vertical-accordion-menu-widget/"><strong>jQuery Vertical Accordion Menu</strong></a> creates vertical accordion menus from any WordPress custom menu.</p>\n<p><a href="http://www.ivinco.com/software/wordpress-sphinx-search/"><strong>WordPress Sphinx Search</strong></a> allows to use Sphinx Search Server power to enable ultra-fast and feature-rich search on WordPress-based websites.</p>\n<img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/weblogtoolscollection/UXMP/~4/fmuoQkBB-QY" height="1" width="1" />";}i:12;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:63:"WPTavern: Using Chrome And WordPress To Publish Saved Bookmarks";s:4:"guid";s:31:"http://www.wptavern.com/?p=5241";s:4:"link";s:115:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/WordpressTavern/~3/oCARKWuyMHU/using-chrome-and-wordpress-to-publish-saved-bookmarks";s:11:"description";s:551:"<p>Here is a <a href="http://www.wptavern.com/forum/resources/2210-free-google-chrome-extension-wordpress-have-your-own.html">cool little extension</a> for Google Chrome that uses the WordPress API to publish saved bookmarks as posts instead of using the Del.icio.us service. It requires WordPress 3.0 and only takes about a minute to setup. Another nice touch is that it uses the Link post format if your theme supports it.</p>\n\n\n<p>No related posts.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/WordpressTavern/~4/oCARKWuyMHU" height="1" width="1" />";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Fri, 08 Apr 2011 23:30:30 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:6:"Jeffro";}s:7:"summary";s:551:"<p>Here is a <a href="http://www.wptavern.com/forum/resources/2210-free-google-chrome-extension-wordpress-have-your-own.html">cool little extension</a> for Google Chrome that uses the WordPress API to publish saved bookmarks as posts instead of using the Del.icio.us service. It requires WordPress 3.0 and only takes about a minute to setup. Another nice touch is that it uses the Link post format if your theme supports it.</p>\n\n\n<p>No related posts.</p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/WordpressTavern/~4/oCARKWuyMHU" height="1" width="1" />";}i:13;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:61:"WPCandy: Inspired Magazine is giving away 26 WordPress themes";s:4:"guid";s:27:"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16727";s:4:"link";s:106:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/wpcandy/~3/k2ZYYPsGtcg/inspired-magazine-is-giving-away-26-wordpress-themes";s:11:"description";s:1457:"<p><a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16727"><img class="size-full wp-image-16729 alignnone" title="Inspired Magazine logo (teaser)" src="http://wpcandy.com/files/2011/04/inspiredmagazinelogo-teaser.png" alt="" width="600" height="220" /></a></p><p>Inspired Magazine has put together a pretty big WordPress theme giveaway: they&#8217;re looking to offload 26 WordPress themes from some very high quality theme shops. I won&#8217;t list them all, but I did see Organic Themes, Press75, Themify, Obox, and StudioPress in there, among many others.</p><p>To throw your hat in the ring, they&#8217;re asking you to tweet out a message and <a title="Inspired Magazine WordPress theme giveaway" href="http://www.inspiredm.com/biggest-wordpress-giveaway/">comment on their post</a> with the theme you&#8217;d most like in your armory. <em>Easy peasy</em>. The contest does end this coming Monday, the 11th, so don&#8217;t dawdle.</p><p>Okay, so they&#8217;re not exactly breaking the mold as far as internet contests go, but it&#8217;s a small price to pay for a free WordPress theme, right?<em> </em>Let us know if you win, so we can enjoy it vicariously through you!</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16727">Inspired Magazine is giving away 26 WordPress themes</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Fri, 08 Apr 2011 22:38:47 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:9:"Ryan Imel";}s:7:"summary";s:1457:"<p><a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16727"><img class="size-full wp-image-16729 alignnone" title="Inspired Magazine logo (teaser)" src="http://wpcandy.com/files/2011/04/inspiredmagazinelogo-teaser.png" alt="" width="600" height="220" /></a></p><p>Inspired Magazine has put together a pretty big WordPress theme giveaway: they&#8217;re looking to offload 26 WordPress themes from some very high quality theme shops. I won&#8217;t list them all, but I did see Organic Themes, Press75, Themify, Obox, and StudioPress in there, among many others.</p><p>To throw your hat in the ring, they&#8217;re asking you to tweet out a message and <a title="Inspired Magazine WordPress theme giveaway" href="http://www.inspiredm.com/biggest-wordpress-giveaway/">comment on their post</a> with the theme you&#8217;d most like in your armory. <em>Easy peasy</em>. The contest does end this coming Monday, the 11th, so don&#8217;t dawdle.</p><p>Okay, so they&#8217;re not exactly breaking the mold as far as internet contests go, but it&#8217;s a small price to pay for a free WordPress theme, right?<em> </em>Let us know if you win, so we can enjoy it vicariously through you!</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16727">Inspired Magazine is giving away 26 WordPress themes</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";}i:14;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:87:"WPCandy: WPBundle unbundles, offers new pricing structure, and separates from WooThemes";s:4:"guid";s:27:"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16721";s:4:"link";s:101:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/wpcandy/~3/7vZRwqD2kGc/wpbundle-unbundles-offers-new-pricing-structure";s:11:"description";s:2715:"<p><a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16721"><img class="size-full wp-image-16723 alignnone" title="WPBundle pricing news (teaser)" src="http://wpcandy.com/files/2011/04/wpbundlebundle-teaser.png" alt="" width="600" height="270" /></a></p><p>WPBundle <a title="WPBundle pricing structure announcement" href="http://www.wpbundle.com/2011/new-wpbundle-pricing/">announced</a> this week that they would be making individual theme purchases available, where previously only their 10 theme bundle could be purchased. Individual themes are available for $50 each, though the bundle of all themes is still around for just $200, down from the previous $250 price tag. Mini-bundles were also teased, though no details are available yet regarding just what these will include.</p><p>The team stresses that individual theme sales include support, updates, child themes, and access to their icon set, same as the previous bundle did. Liam McKay described the reasons for the decision on their blog:</p><blockquote><p>From the start of the project we’ve had a lot of people requesting individual theme sales. We’ve never been against the idea, but there was a few reasons why we didn’t feel right doing this, one of which was our name! It felt strange moving away from bundles, because of that, but we understand the demand and need for cheaper options.</p></blockquote><p>The announcement also included the news that WPBundle is no longer partnering with WooThemes.</p><p><span id="more-16721"></span></p><p>McKay says there are no hard feelings over the split, but that with the new direction WPBundle is headed WooThemes &#8220;didn&#8217;t want to be part of the new direction as they have to focus their attention on their own products.&#8221; WPBundle will now use their own sales and support system, which they are in the process of implementing now.</p><p>Also, have a read through our past WPBundle coverage: WPBundle is one of the first WordPress shops that we were able to watch pretty much from <a title="WPCandy coverage of WPBundle" href="http://wpcandy.com/covers/wpbundle">when they began</a>.</p><p>While we&#8217;re on this topic, what is your stance on theme pricing? Do you prefer buying in bulk via a bundle or a membership, or buying individual themes? If you were calling the shots, what would you say? Where&#8217;s the sweet spot between profitability and user friendliness?</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16721">WPBundle unbundles, offers new pricing structure, and separates from WooThemes</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Fri, 08 Apr 2011 21:50:56 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:9:"Ryan Imel";}s:7:"summary";s:2715:"<p><a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16721"><img class="size-full wp-image-16723 alignnone" title="WPBundle pricing news (teaser)" src="http://wpcandy.com/files/2011/04/wpbundlebundle-teaser.png" alt="" width="600" height="270" /></a></p><p>WPBundle <a title="WPBundle pricing structure announcement" href="http://www.wpbundle.com/2011/new-wpbundle-pricing/">announced</a> this week that they would be making individual theme purchases available, where previously only their 10 theme bundle could be purchased. Individual themes are available for $50 each, though the bundle of all themes is still around for just $200, down from the previous $250 price tag. Mini-bundles were also teased, though no details are available yet regarding just what these will include.</p><p>The team stresses that individual theme sales include support, updates, child themes, and access to their icon set, same as the previous bundle did. Liam McKay described the reasons for the decision on their blog:</p><blockquote><p>From the start of the project we’ve had a lot of people requesting individual theme sales. We’ve never been against the idea, but there was a few reasons why we didn’t feel right doing this, one of which was our name! It felt strange moving away from bundles, because of that, but we understand the demand and need for cheaper options.</p></blockquote><p>The announcement also included the news that WPBundle is no longer partnering with WooThemes.</p><p><span id="more-16721"></span></p><p>McKay says there are no hard feelings over the split, but that with the new direction WPBundle is headed WooThemes &#8220;didn&#8217;t want to be part of the new direction as they have to focus their attention on their own products.&#8221; WPBundle will now use their own sales and support system, which they are in the process of implementing now.</p><p>Also, have a read through our past WPBundle coverage: WPBundle is one of the first WordPress shops that we were able to watch pretty much from <a title="WPCandy coverage of WPBundle" href="http://wpcandy.com/covers/wpbundle">when they began</a>.</p><p>While we&#8217;re on this topic, what is your stance on theme pricing? Do you prefer buying in bulk via a bundle or a membership, or buying individual themes? If you were calling the shots, what would you say? Where&#8217;s the sweet spot between profitability and user friendliness?</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16721">WPBundle unbundles, offers new pricing structure, and separates from WooThemes</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";}i:15;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:65:"WPCandy: WordPress All in One for Dummies now available on Amazon";s:4:"guid";s:27:"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16713";s:4:"link";s:110:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/wpcandy/~3/L_kPMvniorQ/wordpress-all-in-one-for-dummies-now-available-on-amazon";s:11:"description";s:1845:"<p><img class="size-full wp-image-11280 alignnone" title="WordPress All-in-One for Dummies" src="http://wpcandy.com/files/2011/01/wpallinone-teaser.png" alt="" width="600" height="198" /></p><p>Who&#8217;s a dummy? Are you a dummy? Okay, are you a dummy compared to the smart folks who joined forces to write <em>WordPress All in One for Dummies</em>? Insulted or not, if you wanted to you could now pick the book up from Amazon since <a title="WordPress All in One for Dummies on Amazon" href="http://www.amazon.com/WordPress-All-One-Dummies-Sabin-Wilson/dp/0470877014/">it&#8217;s available there this week</a>.</p><p>We&#8217;ve mentioned it <a href="http://wpcandy.com/reports/wordpress-all-in-one-now-available-for-pre-order-on-amazon">once</a> or twice before, but it&#8217;s worth repeating. Lisa Sabin-Wilson, the author of <em>WordPress for Dummies</em>, recruited four other prominent WordPress community members to join her in writing this new book: Cory Miller (of <a href="http://ithemes.com/">iThemes</a>), Kevin Palmer (of <a href="http://www.convertiv.com/">Convertiv</a>), Andrea Rennick (of <a href="http://wpebooks.com/">WPeBooks</a>) and Michael Torbert (of the <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/all-in-one-seo-pack/">All in One SEO Pack</a>). Each author tackled a section devoted to their own area of specialty, and while I haven&#8217;t read it yet I&#8217;m anticipating quite a bit.</p><p>Have you snatched up a copy and dug into <em>All in One</em> yet? If so, share your thoughts on it in the comments.</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16713">WordPress All in One for Dummies now available on Amazon</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Fri, 08 Apr 2011 17:03:18 +0000";s:2:"dc";a:1:{s:7:"creator";s:9:"Ryan Imel";}s:7:"summary";s:1845:"<p><img class="size-full wp-image-11280 alignnone" title="WordPress All-in-One for Dummies" src="http://wpcandy.com/files/2011/01/wpallinone-teaser.png" alt="" width="600" height="198" /></p><p>Who&#8217;s a dummy? Are you a dummy? Okay, are you a dummy compared to the smart folks who joined forces to write <em>WordPress All in One for Dummies</em>? Insulted or not, if you wanted to you could now pick the book up from Amazon since <a title="WordPress All in One for Dummies on Amazon" href="http://www.amazon.com/WordPress-All-One-Dummies-Sabin-Wilson/dp/0470877014/">it&#8217;s available there this week</a>.</p><p>We&#8217;ve mentioned it <a href="http://wpcandy.com/reports/wordpress-all-in-one-now-available-for-pre-order-on-amazon">once</a> or twice before, but it&#8217;s worth repeating. Lisa Sabin-Wilson, the author of <em>WordPress for Dummies</em>, recruited four other prominent WordPress community members to join her in writing this new book: Cory Miller (of <a href="http://ithemes.com/">iThemes</a>), Kevin Palmer (of <a href="http://www.convertiv.com/">Convertiv</a>), Andrea Rennick (of <a href="http://wpebooks.com/">WPeBooks</a>) and Michael Torbert (of the <a href="http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/all-in-one-seo-pack/">All in One SEO Pack</a>). Each author tackled a section devoted to their own area of specialty, and while I haven&#8217;t read it yet I&#8217;m anticipating quite a bit.</p><p>Have you snatched up a copy and dug into <em>All in One</em> yet? If so, share your thoughts on it in the comments.</p><div class="tentblogger-rss-footer"><p>You just finished reading <a href="http://wpcandy.com/?p=16713">WordPress All in One for Dummies now available on Amazon</a> on <a href="http://wpcandy.com" title="WPCandy WordPress community news">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>";}i:16;a:7:{s:5:"title";s:38:"Publisher Blog: AARP Blog on WordPress";s:4:"guid";s:43:"http://publisherblog.automattic.com/?p=1361";s:4:"link";s:70:"http://publisherblog.automattic.com/2011/04/08/aarp-blog-on-wordpress/";s:11:"description";s:2659:"<p>The AARP has launched their blog on <a href="http://vip.wordpress.com/hosting">WordPress.com VIP</a>.</p>\n<p>To recall the sentiment of Beth Carpenter&#8217;s post &#8220;<a href="http://blog.aarp.org/2011/01/25/boomers-on-facebook-twitter-yep-sure-are/">Baby Boomers on Twitter? Yep, sure are</a>&#8220;, to that we say, <strong>Baby Boomers on WordPress? Yep, sure are.</strong></p>\n<p>Welcome!</p>\n<p><a href="http://blog.aarp.org/"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1362" title="Picture 2" src="http://wordpresspublishers.files.wordpress.com/2011/04/picture-2.png?w=640&h=364" alt="" width="640" height="364" /></a></p>\n<p>[Visit the <a href="http://blog.aarp.org/">official AARP blog</a>]</p>\n<p><em>Ready to become a <a href="http://vip.wordpress.com/">VIP Services Client</a>? Some of the <a href="http://vip.wordpress.com/clients">world’s biggest brands rely on WordPress.com VIP Services.</a></em></p>\n<br />  <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/gocomments/wordpresspublishers.wordpress.com/1361/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/comments/wordpresspublishers.wordpress.com/1361/" /></a> <a rel="nofollow" href="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/godelicious/wordpresspublishers.wordpress.com/1361/"><img alt="" border="0" src="http://feeds.wordpress.com/1.0/delicious/wordpresspublishers.wordpress.c